posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked:
I have a couple of questions about Pathweaver. I’ve never used it before and I was wondering what happens when 2 paths are not connected from start to end. Such as like this: Screenshot 2022-03-16 091056 740×976 344 KB compared to when they are connected like this: Screenshot 2022-03-16 091116 860×920 379 KB

Screenshot 2022-03-16 091056 740×976 344 KB

Screenshot 2022-03-16 091056 740×976 344 KB

Screenshot 2022-03-16 091116 860×920 379 KB

Screenshot 2022-03-16 091116 860×920 379 KB

posts.name: Alex
posts.cooked: There is no requirement for paths to start and end at the same place.

posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked: if they don’t start at the same place, I’m guessing that the robot will still execute the path but may be slightly off from the path because the path on the application is in the correct place but the robot will not be. Is that a correct assumption?

posts.name: Alex
posts.cooked: Ya, it doesn’t actually know where it is relative to where the path tells it is. It will just do the path from wherever it starts.

posts.name: Ryan Blue
posts.cooked:
That’s only true if you reset your odometry at the start of each path. If you don’t, the Ramsete controller will attempt to get the robot to the desired pose pretty aggressively due to the sudden increase in error, likely resulting in undesired movement.

Not resetting odometry has the advantage of reducing error stack up at the end of your paths

posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked: does the odometry take in the original pose of the robot before it runs the trajectory? Should I pass in the position on the field to the odometry before each match starts?

posts.name: Ryan Blue
posts.cooked: Before you run your paths, Reset the odometry to the first pose of your first path

posts.name: Joshua Epperson
posts.cooked: Do I need to reset my odometry to the first path when I run EACH path or just when autonomous initializes?

posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked: Does the reverse spline feature make the robot drive backwards until it hits the next waypoint?

posts.name: Kyle Hildebrand
posts.cooked: Yes, the front of the robot should be facing the direction of the blue line, just like the normal splines. The only difference is that the robot travels in the opposite direction the arrows are pointing.

posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked: Does the andThen method of the RamseteCommand class execute the path I set or do I have to call a different method?

posts.name: Joshua Epperson
posts.cooked: andThen() wants a command, the new commandbase from 2020 features inline commands with lambdas () -> code
